<center><A HREF="http://www.shadowydreamer.com/everquest" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="http://www.shadowydreamer.com/artanimation2.gif" border="0"></A>     <A HREF="http://www.shadowydreamer.com/tuxandbunny" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="http://www.shadowydreamer.com/tuxandbunny/images/button.gif" border="0"></A></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usmallcutepuppy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>smallcutepuppy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 313<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/3/02 12:48:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=298.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Manipulation</span><hr size=1> Voskor had warned Kelisk that the Gnome had grown in strength since the last time they'd spoken. He'd half-jokingly teased his friend about his own flounderings in his magical studies. He had also known that such warnings were pointless, and Kelisk would go ahead and charge into battle with his usual bullheadedness. But Kelisk's honor was his own, and it was hardly Voskor's place to stand in his way. He'd taken a seat in the stands to watch the duel, not entirely surprised to see Charizma defeat the patriarch and his wolf.<br>
<br>
Still, it hadn't been a bad matchup. Perhaps defeat would spur Kelisk to attend more diligently to his studies. &quot;I have some business to attend to in the bazaar,&quot; he'd told his friend, &quot;I'll be back a bit later if that's all right?&quot; (ooc: Shrek was on and I'd never seen it before, hehe) Kelisk had agreed readily, and he'd left the two of them at the arena.<br>
<br>
Voskor rather liked the Gnome. Inasmuch as one could like an enemy that one fully intended to slay when it became necessary, anyway. Their conversations were unavoidably tinted with veiled barbs and threats, but he had always come away from them feeling that he had spoken with someone he could understand. A warrior, who understood the tenets of honor, and respect for one's opponent.<br>
<br>
Earlier that very afternoon, he'd met her in the bazaar and asked her about the rumours he'd heard linking her to Gore. She'd replied (and he tried to remember the words as closely as he could, though the translation from foreign tongue made it difficult), &quot;Oh no... Gore showed me power, that's true, but that kind of power is... wrong. It would destroy my soul.&quot; And then, &quot;I hope to change him... there must be a way to save him.&quot;<br>
<br>
No way to save someone from his own delusional insanity, Voskor had thought. <br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
When Voskor had returned to the arena some time later, rather bemused to hear that Kelisk was still there, the sight of Gore killing Sarhea was certainly the last thing he expected to see. The Legionnaire stopped dead in his tracks and shot a puzzled look at Kelisk, who'd at least had the sense to retire to the stands. &quot;Why is he killing the elf wench?&quot; Nevermind, 'why is he here in the first place'; the scene below was far too surreal.<br>
<br>
&quot;Because he is confused and weak of mind,&quot; Kelisk retorted simply, chuckling as Gore turned on the cleric Hateborn, clearly enjoying the show.<br>
<br>
Voskor was too confused to enjoy it. He had thought Gore a traitor because of his blind devotion to the sword. That, at least, he could understand. Misplaced fervor over an imagined blood debt. This... utter carnage... held no reason, no order. It was foreign to his entire way of thinking. He watched as the traitor proceeded to slaughter the League, and proclaimed himself free.<br>
<br>
That, to Voskor's mind, was a more dangerous declaration than anything, as Gore was very clearly insane. If he now perceived himself to have no boundaries and no consequence, the chaos that could fly in his wake was unimaginable.<br>
<br>
&quot;I think he's calmed down now,&quot; he heard Kelisk say, as he hopped down into the arena. If he'd been a hair quicker, Voskor would have grabbed him by his stupid tail and held him back. He couldn't hear the words from where he stood, but he saw Kelisk approach the lunatic as if to say something.<br>
<br>
And of course, Gore struck.<br>
<br>
Self-preservation flew from the Legionnaire's thoughts as he leaped down into the pit. However great a fool Kelisk acted, he was Iksar. He was his friend. His brother in arms. And however futile the attempt be, Voskor was bound by honor to defend him. The irony did not fail to flash through his mind as he coolly drew his weapons and laid into the larger warrior.<br>
<br>
Kelisk fell quickly, and Gore turned to him with furious blows. Voskor gritted his teeth and held his ground, though he was battered through his armor and rent with pain. He would lose the fight. He could see that from the first exchange. But his own skill had grown since they'd last met, and he could see that he was hurting his opponent.<br>
<br>
Gore saw it too. &quot;You've gotten better,&quot; he hissed at a junction when their blades locked. Voskor only smiled grimly and shoved off, following up with another swing. Dimly he heard Charizma telling him to put up a good fight... A vicious slash drew a torrent of blood from Voskor's side, and the warrior saw red. He loosed a roar of defiance and flew into a berserker fury of flashing weapons, determined to do as much damage as he could before he fell.<br>
<br>
And suddenly the pain was gone. His wounds closed of their own accord and life flowed once more into his limbs. His discipline faltered momentarily in surprise, and he needed a second to catch up to the sight of Gore suddenly detaching from him and laying into the human in purple. Hateborn. Had... healed him? Then the League and their brat god must truly have forsaken him. Burning every bridge in sight, Gore, he thought grimly to himself as he leaped after him again.<br>
<br>
The battle became a blur as the rest of the League - perhaps finally spurred at the sight of a single warrior standing up to him, he thought dryly - joined in to cut the traitor down. To his only half-surprise, Voskor saw a familiar glint of steel and scale and Saurix beating on Gore from the side. &quot;I should have known you'd come,&quot; he tried to hiss, but he couldn't know if the words escaped, as a final blow sent him crashing to the earth and consciousness fled.<br>
<br>
He awoke in the tunnel at the gates to the pit. Saurix and Kelisk were beside him. &quot;What happened?&quot; he groaned, sitting up and trying to shake the rattling out of his skull. Through the portcullis he could see Gore still standing. &quot;Someone healed him?&quot; he asked puzzledly.<br>
<br>
&quot;I think it was Thrads,&quot; Saurix muttered, busy binding his own wounds. Voskor quickly knelt to assist him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Mistmoore's little herald? What's he got to do with any of this?&quot; That, no one could answer. They bound up Saurix as well as they could and prepared to let the battle be rejoined.<br>
<br>
Too late. &quot;I win,&quot; Gore shouted simply, and fled the arena to embark on who-knew-what new crusade.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
Voskor hung around the lingering Leaguers and Thrads long enough to hear what they had to say, but he kept his own involvement in the conversation to corrections of fallacies. Mainly Thrads'. The little rat never did come out and say how he was wrapped up in Gore and why he'd gotten involved in the first place. He seemed to be under the impression that Gore loved Charizma, or Sarhea, or the other way around, or something.<br>
<br>
When Charizma had cried and said she only wanted to free him, he had almost felt sympathy. After all, he himself had always thought that Gore's treachery was entirely centered on the sword, and not realized until now that his insanity had grown much deeper than that. He had kept his mouth shut while Kelisk insulted her, because it didn't seem like the right thing to do.<br>
<br>
But then she had said that Iksar could never understand things like caring for one another. And any trace of sympathy had been squelched by indignation. He, who every moment's breath was devoted for love of Cabilis...! &quot;You,&quot; he had snarled, &quot;do not presume to know our thoughts. It is you creatures of chaos who cannot comprehend devotion to one's kind.&quot; Hadn't she told him that very day that she had parted ways with the Tinkers to pursue her own ends? How dare she speak to him in such a manner.<br>
<br>
And even then, he had tossed the fruit at her feet, having noticed her pale shivering and longing glances at his food packs. Though the scale and reasons may have been different, she had fought at least as hard as he had that afternoon, and the gesture was not as entirely mocking as he made it out to be. Somewhere he hoped that the warrior he thought he had understood in her would see that.<br>
<br>
